2–1486","1405–1485":"1405–1485","1436–1450":"1436–1450","1371–1465":"1371–1465","1372–1460":"1372–1460","25 May 1486":"25 May 1486","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1436":"1436","26 June 1485":"26 June 1485","April 1465":"April 1465","1412":"1412","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1485":"1485","about 1412":"about 1412","1405":"1405","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","North Marston, Buckinghamshire, England":"North Marston, Buckinghamshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Bosworth, Leichestershire, England":"France","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England":"Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Byron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Byram (Yorkshire), named with Old English <i>bȳrum</i> ‘at the cattle sheds’, dative plural of <i>bȳre</i> ‘byre’. This name has occasionally been adopted as a Jewish surname, presumably as an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish name."],"variants":[{"name":"Byrom","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]},{"name":"Byrum","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]},{"name":"Byram","meanings":["English: variant of   Byron  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":43,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Margaret Byron was born about 1412, in Clayton, Lancashire, England, her father, John de Byron III, was 42 and her mother, Margery Booth, was 41. She had at least 1 son with Sir William De Atherton IV. She died on 25 May 1486, in Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1412–25 May 1486":"umbes 1412–25. mai 1486","1412–1486":"1412–1486","1405–1485":"1405–1485","1436–1450":"1436–1450","1371–1465":"1371–1465","1372–1460":"1372–1460","25 May 1486":"25. mai 1486","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1436":"1436","26 June 1485":"26. juuni 1485","April 1465":"aprill 1465","1412":"1412","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1485":"1485","about 1412":"umbes 1412","1405":"1405","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","North Marston, Buckinghamshire, England":"North Marston, Buckinghamshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bosworth, Leichestershire, England":"Prantsusmaa","Derby, Derbyshire